  "facts": [
    {
      "id": 1,
      "text": "Cedar Grove earned its name from the cedar trees that once lined the area, dating back to early 1900s settlement.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        5
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://grokipedia.com/page/cedar_grove_florida"
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "In 2008, residents voted to dissolve the town, making it the first Florida town disincorporated by citizen vote.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        2
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cedar_Grove%2C_Florida"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "The dissolution ordinance took effect at 8:00 AM on Oct 22, 2008, disbanding the police department and transferring assets to Bay County.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        3
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cedar_Grove%2C_Florida"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "After dissolution, Bay County Sheriff’s Office added four deputies to cover Cedar Grove.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        6
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://grokipedia.com/page/cedar_grove_florida"
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "text": "Cedar Grove sits in Florida’s Panhandle and enjoys a humid subtropical climate with hot, humid summers and mild winters.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        10
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://grokipedia.com/page/cedar_grove_florida"
    },
    {
      "id": 6,
      "text": "The area is prone to tropical cyclones; a 1929 Category 4 hurricane once brought gusts up to 198 mph, and projected 30‑year gusts could reach 169 mph.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
